# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ndjson
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ndjson/data-stream] In connection-oriented communication, a **data stream** is the transmission of a sequence of digitally encoded signals to convey information.
[src:ndjson/data-stream] Typically, the transmitted symbols are grouped into a series of packets.
[src:ndjson/data-stream] Most data transmitted over the Internet is transmitted as a data stream.
[src:ndjson/data-stream] Using a mobile phone to have a conversation transmits the sound as a data stream.
[src:ndjson/data-stream] 2. $\Delta$ is a sequence of positive real time intervals.
[src:ndjson/data-stream] Data Stream contains different sets of data, that depend on the chosen data format.
[src:ndjson/data-stream] A **data point** is a tag that collects information about a certain action, performed by a user on a website.
[src:ndjson/data-stream] Data points exists in two types, the values of which are used to create appropriate audiences.
[src:ndjson/data-stream] Information gathered out of websites are based on user behavior.
[src:ndjson/data-stream] Data providers deliver both personal or non-personal information.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] A **delimited text file** is a text file that stores data as DSV.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] Such a file can be classified as a flat-file database if, in fact, the data is database-like – accessing individual rows is meaningful.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] A commonly used alternative for text data is fixed-width where each column has the same number of characters – limiting the length of each field value.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] In contrast, DSV supports field values of any length.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] DSV is a categorization of data format, not a particular format.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] To be useful, a convention must be established that defines the precise format.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] In general a format is categorized as DSV if it is lines of delimiter-separated values (where lines are newline-separated).
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] The first row is sometimes a special record containing the column names.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] Any character may be used to separate field values, and the more commonly used include comma, tab, colon, vertical bar (a.k.a. pipe) and space.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] ASCII and Unicode include control characters that are intended to be used as delimiters: File Separator, Group Separator, Record Separator, and Unit Separator.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] Use of these in DSV data is relatively uncommon although the MARC 21 bibliographic data format does.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] Two commonly-used sub-categories of DSV, comma-separated values (CSV) and tab-separated values (TSV), are supported by many software packages including many spreadsheet and statistical applications.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] Some can import such data even without the user describing the format – such as which character to use as the delimiter.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] Even though such an application may more directly support a more capable and possibly proprietary internal data model (for example, accdb or xlsx), they can map DSV data to their internal data model.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] A particular challenge of DSV is delimiter collision – what happens when the delimiter character is embedded in a field value without accommodation for doing so.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] The character is interpreted as a separator – splitting a single, logical value into two.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] Some DSV conventions simply disallow a delimiter in a value while others provide a mechanism that allows for embedding delimiters.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] A commonly-used way to avoid delimiter collision is to enclose a field value in double quotes.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] A convention could require this for all values or it could be optional so that it might only be used for values that have an embedded delimiter.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] Collision can be avoided if the convention disallows the delimiter in a field value; the tacit implication if the convention provides no way to avoid collision.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] Using a relatively unusual character (e.g. tilde `~`) limits the impact on possible field values.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] But, even though a character may seem unusual, in practice, it might be used and then result in a processing error.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] In the following example, the table is formatted per typical CSV: fields separated by a comma.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] Each field value is enclosed in double quotes so that a field value can contain a comma.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] The comma in `"Bloggs, Fred"` is not a value separator because the text is enclosed in double-quotes.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] Some formats allow newline to be included in a value via this mechanism.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] To encode a double quote in a value, two double quotes are used where the first one acts as an escape character so that the second one is interpreted as a double quote instead of field begin or end.
[src:ndjson/delimiter-separated-values] The value `"Muniz, Alvin ""Hank"""` is interpreted as `Muniz, Alvin "Hank"`.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] JSON is a popular format for exchanging object data between systems.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] Frequently there's a need for a stream of objects to be sent over a single connection, such as a stock ticker or application log records.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] In these cases there's a need to identify where one JSON encoded object ends and the next begins.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] Line-delimited JSON works very well with traditional line-oriented tools.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] Concatenated JSON works with pretty-printed JSON but requires more effort and complexity to parse.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] It doesn't work well with traditional line-oriented tools.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] Concatenated JSON streaming is a superset of line-delimited JSON streaming.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] Length-prefixed JSON works with pretty-printed JSON.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] It doesn't work well with traditional line-oriented tools, but may offer performance advantages over line-delimited or concatenated streaming.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] Streaming makes use of the fact that the JSON format does not allow return and newline characters within primitive values (in strings those must be escaped as `\r` and `\n`, respectively) and that most JSON formatters default to not including any whitespace, including returns and newlines.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] These features allow the newline character or return and newline character sequence to be used as a delimiter.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] The use of a newline as a delimiter enables this format to work very well with traditional line-oriented Unix tools.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] which is very easy to sort by date, grep for usernames, actions, IP addresses, etc.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] Line-delimited JSON can be read by a parser that can handle concatenated JSON.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] Concatenated JSON that contains newlines *within* a JSON object can't be read by a line-delimited JSON parser.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] The terms "line-delimited JSON" and "newline-delimited JSON" are often used without clarifying if embedded newlines are supported.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] In the past the newline delimited JSON specification allowed comments to be embedded if the first two characters of a given line were "//".
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] This could not be used with standard JSON parsers if comments were included.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] Current version of the specification ("NDJSON - Newline delimited JSON ") no longer includes comments.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] Concatenated JSON can be converted into line-delimited JSON by a suitable JSON utility such as jq.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] Record separator-delimited JSON streaming allows JSON text sequences to be delimited without the requirement that the JSON formatter exclude whitespace.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] Since JSON text sequences cannot contain control characters, a record separator character can be used to delimit the sequences.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] In addition, it is suggested that each JSON text sequence be followed by a line feed character to allow proper handling of top-level JSON objects that are not self delimiting (numbers, true, false, and null).
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] This format is also known as JSON Text Sequences or MIME type `application/json-seq`, and is formally described in IETF RFC 7464.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] Concatenated JSON streaming allows the sender to simply write each JSON object into the stream with no delimiters.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] It relies on the receiver using a parser that can recognize and *emit* each JSON object as the terminating character is parsed.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] Concatenated JSON isn't a new format, it's simply a name for streaming multiple JSON objects without any delimiters.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] The advantage of this format is that it can handle JSON objects that have been formatted with embedded newline characters, e.g., pretty-printed for human readability.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] Implementations that rely on line-based input may require a newline character after each JSON object in order for the object to be emitted by the parser in a timely manner.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] (Otherwise the line may remain in the input buffer without being passed to the parser.) This is rarely recognised as an issue because terminating JSON objects with a newline character is very common.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] Length-prefixed or framed JSON streaming allows the sender to explicitly state the length of each message.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] It relies on the receiver using a parser that can recognize each length *n* and then read the following *n* bytes to parse as JSON.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] The advantage of this format is that it can speed up parsing due to the fact that the exact length of each message is explicitly stated, rather than forcing the parser to search for delimiters.
[src:ndjson/json-streaming] Length-prefixed JSON is also well-suited for TCP applications, where a single "message" may be divided into arbitrary chunks, because the prefixed length tells the parser exactly how many bytes to expect before attempting to parse a JSON string.
[src:ndjson/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:ndjson/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:ndjson/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:ndjson/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:ndjson/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:ndjson/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:ndjson/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:ndjson/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:ndjson/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:ndjson/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:ndjson/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:ndjson/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:ndjson/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:ndjson/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:ndjson/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:ndjson/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:ndjson/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:ndjson/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:ndjson/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:ndjson/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:ndjson/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:ndjson/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:ndjson/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:ndjson/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:ndjson/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:ndjson/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:ndjson/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:ndjson/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:ndjson/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:ndjson/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:ndjson/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:ndjson/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:ndjson/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:ndjson/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:ndjson/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:ndjson/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:ndjson/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:ndjson/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:ndjson/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:ndjson/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:ndjson/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:ndjson/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:ndjson/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:ndjson/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:ndjson/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:ndjson/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:ndjson/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:ndjson/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:ndjson/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:ndjson/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:ndjson/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:ndjson/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:ndjson/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:ndjson/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:ndjson/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:ndjson/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:ndjson/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:ndjson/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:ndjson/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:ndjson/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:ndjson/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:ndjson/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:ndjson/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:ndjson/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:ndjson/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:ndjson/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:ndjson/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:ndjson/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:ndjson/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:ndjson/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:ndjson/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:ndjson/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:ndjson/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:ndjson/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:ndjson/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:ndjson/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:ndjson/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:ndjson/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:ndjson/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:ndjson/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:ndjson/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:ndjson/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:ndjson/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:ndjson/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:ndjson/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:ndjson/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:ndjson/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:ndjson/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:ndjson/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:ndjson/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:ndjson/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:ndjson/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:ndjson/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:ndjson/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:ndjson/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:ndjson/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:ndjson/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:ndjson/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:ndjson/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:ndjson/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:ndjson/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:ndjson/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:ndjson/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:ndjson/log-file] In computing, **logging** is the act of keeping a log of events that occur in a computer system, such as problems, errors or broad information on current operations.
[src:ndjson/log-file] These events may occur in the operating system or in other software.
[src:ndjson/log-file] A message or *log entry* is recorded for each such event.
[src:ndjson/log-file] These log messages can then be used to monitor and understand the operation of the system, to debug problems, or during an audit.
[src:ndjson/log-file] Logging is particularly important in multi-user software, to have a central overview of the operation of the system.
[src:ndjson/log-file] In the simplest case, messages are written to a file, called a *log file*.
[src:ndjson/log-file] Alternatively, the messages may be written to a dedicated logging system or to a log management software, where it is stored in a database or on a different computer system.
[src:ndjson/log-file] Specifically, a *transaction log* is a log of the communications between a system and the users of that system, or a data collection method that automatically captures the type, content, or time of transactions made by a person from a terminal with that system.
[src:ndjson/log-file] For Web searching, a transaction log is an electronic record of interactions that have occurred during a searching episode between a Web search engine and users searching for information on that Web search engine.
[src:ndjson/log-file] Many operating systems, software frameworks and programs include a logging system.
[src:ndjson/log-file] A widely used logging standard is Syslog, defined in IETF RFC 5424.
[src:ndjson/log-file] The Syslog standard enables a dedicated, standardized subsystem to generate, filter, record, and analyze log messages.
[src:ndjson/log-file] This relieves software developers of having to design and code their ad hoc logging systems.
[src:ndjson/log-file] It can also be useful to combine log file entries from multiple sources.
[src:ndjson/log-file] It is a different combination that may yield between with related events on different servers.
[src:ndjson/log-file] Other solutions employ network-wide querying and reporting.
[src:ndjson/log-file] Most database systems maintain some kind of *transaction log*, which are not mainly intended as an audit trail for later analysis, and are not intended to be human-readable.
[src:ndjson/log-file] These logs record changes to the stored data to allow the database to recover from crashes or other data errors and maintain the stored data in a consistent state.
[src:ndjson/log-file] Thus, database systems usually have both general event logs and transaction logs.
[src:ndjson/log-file] The use of data stored in transaction logs of Web search engines, Intranets, and websites can provide valuable insight into understanding the information-searching process of online searchers.
[src:ndjson/log-file] This understanding can enlighten information system design, interface development, and devising the information architecture for content collections.
[src:ndjson/log-file] Message logs are almost universally plain text files, but IM and VoIP clients (which support textual chat, e.g.
[src:ndjson/log-file] Skype) might save them in HTML files or in a custom format to ease reading or enable encryption.
[src:ndjson/log-file] Instant messaging and VoIP clients often offer the chance to store encrypted logs to enhance the user's privacy.
[src:ndjson/log-file] These logs require a password to be decrypted and viewed, and they are often handled by their respective writing application.
[src:ndjson/log-file] Some privacy focused messaging services, such as Signal, record minimal logs about users, limiting their information to connection times.
[src:ndjson/log-file] A *server log* is a log file (or several files) automatically created and maintained by a server consisting of a list of activities it performed.
[src:ndjson/log-file] A typical example is a web server log which maintains a history of page requests.
[src:ndjson/log-file] The W3C maintains a standard format (the Common Log Format) for web server log files, but other proprietary formats exist.
[src:ndjson/log-file] Some servers can log information to computer readable formats (such as JSON) versus the human readable standard.
[src:ndjson/log-file] More recent entries are typically appended to the end of the file.
[src:ndjson/log-file] Information about the request, including client IP address, request date/time, page requested, HTTP code, bytes served, user agent, and referrer are typically added.
[src:ndjson/log-file] This data can be combined into a single file, or separated into distinct logs, such as an access log, error log, or referrer log.
[src:ndjson/log-file] However, server logs typically do not collect user-specific information.
[src:ndjson/log-file] These files are usually not accessible to general Internet users, only to the webmaster or other administrative person of an Internet service.
[src:ndjson/log-file] A statistical analysis of the server log may be used to examine traffic patterns by time of day, day of week, referrer, or user agent.
[src:ndjson/log-file] Efficient web site administration, adequate hosting resources and the fine tuning of sales efforts can be aided by analysis of the web server logs.
[src:ndjson/serialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:ndjson/serialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:ndjson/serialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:ndjson/serialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:ndjson/serialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:ndjson/serialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:ndjson/serialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Inherent to any serialization scheme is that, because the encoding of the data is by definition serial, extracting one part of the serialized data structure requires that the entire object be read from start to end, and reconstructed.
[src:ndjson/serialization] In many applications, this linearity is an asset, because it enables simple, common I/O interfaces to be utilized to hold and pass on the state of an object.
[src:ndjson/serialization] In applications where higher performance is an issue, it can make sense to expend more effort to deal with a more complex, non-linear storage organization.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Even on a single machine, primitive pointer objects are too fragile to save because the objects to which they point may be reloaded to a different location in memory.
[src:ndjson/serialization] To deal with this, the serialization process includes a step called *unswizzling* or *pointer unswizzling*, where direct pointer references are converted to references based on name or position.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The deserialization process includes an inverse step called *pointer swizzling*.
[src:ndjson/serialization] It is not necessary to actually build the prior copy because differences can be detected on the fly, a technique called differential execution.
[src:ndjson/serialization] This is useful in the programming of user interfaces whose contents are time-varying — graphical objects can be created, removed, altered, or made to handle input events without necessarily having to write separate code to do those things.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Serialization breaks the opacity of an abstract data type by potentially exposing private implementation details.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Trivial implementations which serialize all data members may violate encapsulation.
[src:ndjson/serialization] To discourage competitors from making compatible products, publishers of proprietary software often keep the details of their programs' serialization formats a trade secret.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Some deliberately obfuscate or even encrypt the serialized data.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Yet, interoperability requires that applications be able to understand each other's serialization formats.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Therefore, remote method call architectures such as CORBA define their serialization formats in detail.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Many institutions, such as archives and libraries, attempt to future proof their backup archives—in particular, database dumps—by storing them in some relatively human-readable serialized format.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The Xerox Network Systems Courier technology in the early 1980s influenced the first widely adopted standard.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Sun Microsystems published the External Data Representation (XDR) in 1987.
[src:ndjson/serialization] XDR is an open format, and standardized as STD 67 (RFC 4506) by IETF.
[src:ndjson/serialization] In the late 1990s, a push to provide an alternative to the standard serialization protocols started: XML, an SGML subset, was used to produce a human-readable text-based encoding.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Such an encoding can be useful for persistent objects that may be read and understood by humans or communicated to other systems regardless of programming language.
[src:ndjson/serialization] It has the disadvantage of losing the more compact, byte-stream-based encoding, but by this point larger storage and transmission capacities made file size less of a concern than in the early days of computing.
[src:ndjson/serialization] In the 2000s, XML was often used for asynchronous transfer of structured data between client and server in Ajax web applications.
[src:ndjson/serialization] XML is an open format and standardized as a W3C recommendation.
[src:ndjson/serialization] JSON is a lightweight plain-text alternative to XML and is also commonly used for client-server communication in web applications.
[src:ndjson/serialization] JSON is based on JavaScript syntax but is independent of JavaScript and supported in many other programming languages.
[src:ndjson/serialization] YAML is a strict superset of JSON and includes additional features such as a data type tags, support for cyclic data structures, indentation-sensitive syntax, and multiple forms of scalar data quoting.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Property lists are used for serialization by NeXTSTEP, GNUstep, macOS, and iOS frameworks.
[src:ndjson/serialization] *Property list*, or *p-list* for short, doesn't refer to a single serialization format but instead several different variants, some human-readable and one binary.
[src:ndjson/serialization] For large volume scientific datasets, such as satellite data and output of numerical climate, weather, or ocean models, specific binary serialization standards have been developed, e.g.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Several object-oriented programming languages directly support *object serialization* (or *object archival*), either by syntactic sugar elements or providing a standard interface for doing so.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The languages which do so include Ruby, Smalltalk, Python, PHP, Objective-C, Delphi, Java, and the .NET family of languages.
[src:ndjson/serialization] There are also libraries available that add serialization support to languages that lack native support for it.
[src:ndjson/serialization] C and C++ do not provide serialization as any sort of high-level construct, but both languages support writing any of the built-in data types, as well as plain old data structs, as binary data.
[src:ndjson/serialization] As such, it is usually trivial to write custom serialization functions.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Moreover, compiler-based solutions, such as the ODB ORM system for C++ and the gSOAP toolkit for C and C++, are capable of automatically producing serialization code with few or no modifications to class declarations.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Other popular serialization frameworks are Boost.Serialization from the Boost Framework, the S11n framework, and Cereal.
[src:ndjson/serialization] MFC framework (Microsoft) also provides serialization methodology as part of its Document-View architecture.
[src:ndjson/serialization] With the introduction of reflective programming to C++26, serialization has been greatly simplified.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Reflection allows for compile-time serialization of, for instance, JSON into a `struct` with corresponding structure.
[src:ndjson/serialization] CFML allows data structures to be serialized to WDDX with the `<cfwddx>` tag and to JSON with the SerializeJSON() function.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Delphi provides a built-in mechanism for serialization of components (also called persistent objects), which is fully integrated with its IDE.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The component's contents are saved to a DFM file and reloaded on-the-fly.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Go natively supports unmarshalling/marshalling of JSON and XML data.
[src:ndjson/serialization] There are also third-party modules that support YAML and Protocol Buffers.
[src:ndjson/serialization] In Haskell, serialization is supported for types that are members of the Read and Show type classes.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Every type that is a member of the `Read` type class defines a function that will extract the data from the string representation of the dumped data.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The `Show` type class, in turn, contains the `show` function from which a string representation of the object can be generated.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The programmer need not define the functions explicitly—merely declaring a type to be deriving Read or deriving Show, or both, can make the compiler generate the appropriate functions for many cases (but not all: function types, for example, cannot automatically derive Show or Read).
[src:ndjson/serialization] The auto-generated instance for Show also produces valid source code, so the same Haskell value can be generated by running the code produced by show in, for example, a Haskell interpreter.
[src:ndjson/serialization] For more efficient serialization, there are haskell libraries that allow high-speed serialization in binary format, e.g. binary.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Java provides automatic serialization which requires that the object be marked by implementing the `java.io.Serializable` interface.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Implementing the interface marks the class as "okay to serialize", and Java then handles serialization internally.
[src:ndjson/serialization] There are no serialization methods defined on the `Serializable` interface, but a serializable class can optionally define methods with certain special names and signatures that if defined, will be called as part of the serialization/deserialization process.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The language also allows the developer to override the serialization process more thoroughly by implementing another interface, the `Externalizable` interface, which includes two special methods that are used to save and restore the object's state.
[src:ndjson/serialization] There are three primary reasons why objects are not serializable by default and must implement the `Serializable` interface to access Java's serialization mechanism.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Firstly, not all objects capture useful semantics in a serialized state.
[src:ndjson/serialization] For example, a `Thread` object is tied to the state of the current JVM.
[src:ndjson/serialization] There is no context in which a deserialized `Thread` object would maintain useful semantics.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Secondly, the serialized state of an object forms part of its class' compatibility contract.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Maintaining compatibility between versions of serializable classes requires additional effort and consideration.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Therefore, making a class serializable needs to be a deliberate design decision and not a default condition.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Lastly, serialization allows access to non-transient private members of a class that are not otherwise accessible.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Classes containing sensitive information (for example, a password) should not be serializable nor externalizable.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The standard encoding method uses a recursive graph-based translation of the object's class descriptor and serializable fields into a byte stream.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Primitives as well as non-transient, non-static referenced objects are encoded into the stream.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Each object that is referenced by the serialized object via a field that is not marked as `transient` must also be serialized; and if any object in the complete graph of non-transient object references is not serializable, then serialization will fail.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The developer can influence this behavior by marking objects as transient, or by redefining the serialization for an object so that some portion of the reference graph is truncated and not serialized.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Java does not use constructor to serialize objects.
[src:ndjson/serialization] It is possible to serialize Java objects through JDBC and store them into a database.
[src:ndjson/serialization] While Swing components do implement the Serializable interface, they are not guaranteed to be portable between different versions of the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:ndjson/serialization] As such, a Swing component, or any component which inherits it, may be serialized to a byte stream, but it is not guaranteed that this will be re-constitutable on another machine.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Since ECMAScript 5.1, JavaScript has included the built-in `JSON` object and its methods `JSON.parse()` and `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Although JSON is originally based on a subset of JavaScript, there are boundary cases where JSON is not valid JavaScript.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Specifically, JSON allows the Unicode line terminators U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR to appear unescaped in quoted strings, while ECMAScript 2018 and older does not.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Julia implements serialization through the `serialize()` / `deserialize()` modules, intended to work within the same version of Julia, and/or instance of the same system image.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The `HDF5.jl` package offers a more stable alternative, using a documented format and common library with wrappers for different languages, while the default serialization format is suggested to have been designed rather with maximal performance for network communication in mind.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Generally a Lisp data structure can be serialized with the functions "`read`" and "`print`".
[src:ndjson/serialization] A variable foo containing, for example, a list of arrays would be printed by `(print foo)`.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Similarly an object can be read from a stream named s by `(read s)`.
[src:ndjson/serialization] These two parts of the Lisp implementation are called the Printer and the Reader.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The output of "`print`" is human readable; it uses lists demarked by parentheses, for example: `(4 2.9 "x" y)`.
[src:ndjson/serialization] In many types of Lisp, including Common Lisp, the printer cannot represent every type of data because it is not clear how to do so.
[src:ndjson/serialization] In Common Lisp for example the printer cannot print CLOS objects.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Instead the programmer may write a method on the generic function `print-object`, this will be invoked when the object is printed.
[src:ndjson/serialization] This is somewhat similar to the method used in Ruby.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Lisp code itself is written in the syntax of the reader, called read syntax.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Most languages use separate and different parsers to deal with code and data, Lisp only uses one.
[src:ndjson/serialization] A file containing lisp code may be read into memory as a data structure, transformed by another program, then possibly executed or written out, such as in a read–eval–print loop.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Not all readers/writers support cyclic, recursive or shared structures.
[src:ndjson/serialization] .NET has several serializers designed by Microsoft.
[src:ndjson/serialization] There are also many serializers by third parties.
[src:ndjson/serialization] OCaml's standard library provides marshalling through the `Marshal` module and the Pervasives functions `output_value` and `input_value`.
[src:ndjson/serialization] While OCaml programming is statically type-checked, uses of the `Marshal` module may break type guarantees, as there is no way to check whether an unmarshalled stream represents objects of the expected type.
[src:ndjson/serialization] In OCaml it is difficult to marshal a function or a data structure which contains a function (e.g. an object which contains a method), because executable code in functions cannot be transmitted across different programs.
[src:ndjson/serialization] (There is a flag to marshal the code position of a function but it can only be unmarshalled in exactly the same program).
[src:ndjson/serialization] The standard marshalling functions can preserve sharing and handle cyclic data, which can be configured by a flag.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Several Perl modules available from CPAN provide serialization mechanisms, including `Storable` , `JSON::XS` and `FreezeThaw`.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Storable includes functions to serialize and deserialize Perl data structures to and from files or Perl scalars.
[src:ndjson/serialization] In addition to serializing directly to files, `Storable` includes the `freeze` function to return a serialized copy of the data packed into a scalar, and `thaw` to deserialize such a scalar.
[src:ndjson/serialization] This is useful for sending a complex data structure over a network socket or storing it in a database.
[src:ndjson/serialization] When serializing structures with `Storable`, there are network safe functions that always store their data in a format that is readable on any computer at a small cost of speed.
[src:ndjson/serialization] These functions are named `nstore`, `nfreeze`, etc.
[src:ndjson/serialization] There are no "n" functions for deserializing these structures — the regular `thaw` and `retrieve` deserialize structures serialized with the "`n`" functions and their machine-specific equivalents.
[src:ndjson/serialization] PHP originally implemented serialization through the built-in `serialize()` and `unserialize()` functions.
[src:ndjson/serialization] PHP can serialize any of its data types except resources (file pointers, sockets, etc.).
[src:ndjson/serialization] The built-in `unserialize()` function is often dangerous when used on completely untrusted data.
[src:ndjson/serialization] For objects, there are two "magic methods" that can be implemented within a class — `__sleep()` and `__wakeup()` — that are called from within `serialize()` and `unserialize()`, respectively, that can clean up and restore an object.
[src:ndjson/serialization] For example, it may be desirable to close a database connection on serialization and restore the connection on deserialization; this functionality would be handled in these two magic methods.
[src:ndjson/serialization] They also permit the object to pick which properties are serialized.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Since PHP 5.1, there is an object-oriented serialization mechanism for objects, the `Serializable` interface.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Prolog's *term* structure, which is the only data structure of the language, can be serialized out through the built-in predicate `write_term/3` and serialized-in through the built-in predicates `read/1` and `read_term/2`.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The resulting stream is uncompressed text (in some encoding determined by configuration of the target stream), with any free variables in the term represented by placeholder variable names.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The predicate `write_term/3` is standardized in the ISO Specification for Prolog (ISO/IEC 13211-1) on pages 59 ff.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Therefore it is expected that terms serialized-out by one implementation can be serialized-in by another without ambiguity or surprises.
[src:ndjson/serialization] In practice, implementation-specific extensions (e.g.
[src:ndjson/serialization] SWI-Prolog's dictionaries) may use non-standard term structures, so interoperability may break in edge cases.
[src:ndjson/serialization] As examples, see the corresponding manual pages for SWI-Prolog, SICStus Prolog, GNU Prolog.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Whether and how serialized terms received over the network are checked against a specification (after deserialization from the character stream has happened) is left to the implementer.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Prolog's built-in Definite Clause Grammars can be applied at that stage.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The core general serialization mechanism is the `pickle` standard library module, alluding to the database systems term *pickling* to describe data serialization (*unpickling* for *deserializing*).
[src:ndjson/serialization] Pickle uses a simple stack-based virtual machine that records the instructions used to reconstruct the object.
[src:ndjson/serialization] It is a cross-version customizable but unsafe (not secure against erroneous or malicious data) serialization format.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Malformed or maliciously constructed data, may cause the deserializer to import arbitrary modules and instantiate any object.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The standard library also includes modules serializing to standard data formats: `json` (with built-in support for basic scalar and collection types and able to support arbitrary types via encoding and decoding hooks).
[src:ndjson/serialization] `plistlib` (with support for both binary and XML property list formats).
[src:ndjson/serialization] `xdrlib` (with support for the External Data Representation (XDR) standard as described in RFC 1014).
[src:ndjson/serialization] Finally, it is recommended that an object's `__repr__` be evaluable in the right environment, making it a rough match for Common Lisp's `print-object`.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Not all object types can be pickled automatically, especially ones that hold operating system resources like file handles, but users can register custom "reduction" and construction functions to support the pickling and unpickling of arbitrary types.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Pickle was originally implemented as the pure Python `pickle` module, but, in versions of Python prior to 3.0, the `cPickle` module (also a built-in) offers improved performance (up to 1000 times faster).
[src:ndjson/serialization] The `cPickle` was adapted from the Unladen Swallow project.
[src:ndjson/serialization] In Python 3, users should always import the standard version, which attempts to import the accelerated version and falls back to the pure Python version.
[src:ndjson/serialization] R has the function `dput` which writes an ASCII text representation of an R object to a file or connection.
[src:ndjson/serialization] A representation can be read from a file using `dget`.
[src:ndjson/serialization] More specific, the function `serialize` serializes an R object to a connection, the output being a raw vector coded in hexadecimal format.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The `unserialize` function allows to read an object from a connection or a raw vector.
[src:ndjson/serialization] REBOL will serialize to file (`save/all`) or to a `string!` (`mold/all`).
[src:ndjson/serialization] Strings and files can be deserialized using the polymorphic `load` function.
[src:ndjson/serialization] `RProtoBuf` provides cross-language data serialization in R, using Protocol Buffers.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Ruby includes the standard module `Marshal` with 2 methods `dump` and `load`, akin to the standard Unix utilities `dump` and `restore`.
[src:ndjson/serialization] These methods serialize to the standard class `String`, that is, they effectively become a sequence of bytes.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Some objects cannot be serialized (doing so would raise a `TypeError` exception): bindings, procedure objects, instances of class IO, singleton objects and interfaces.
[src:ndjson/serialization] If a class requires custom serialization (for example, it requires certain cleanup actions done on dumping / restoring), it can be done by implementing 2 methods: `_dump` and `_load`.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The instance method `_dump` should return a `String` object containing all the information necessary to reconstitute objects of this class and all referenced objects up to a maximum depth given as an integer parameter (a value of -1 implies that depth checking should be disabled).
[src:ndjson/serialization] The class method `_load` should take a `String` and return an object of this class.
[src:ndjson/serialization] `Serde` is the most widely used library, or crate, for serialization in Rust which provides the `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits.
[src:ndjson/serialization] In general, non-recursive and non-sharing objects can be stored and retrieved in a human readable form using the `storeOn:`/`readFrom:` protocol.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The `storeOn:` method generates the text of a Smalltalk expression which – when evaluated using `readFrom:` – recreates the original object.
[src:ndjson/serialization] This scheme is special, in that it uses a procedural description of the object, not the data itself.
[src:ndjson/serialization] It is therefore very flexible, allowing for classes to define more compact representations.
[src:ndjson/serialization] However, in its original form, it does not handle cyclic data structures or preserve the identity of shared references (i.e. two references a single object will be restored as references to two equal, but not identical copies).
[src:ndjson/serialization] For this, various portable and non-portable alternatives exist.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Some of them are specific to a particular Smalltalk implementation or class library.
[src:ndjson/serialization] There are several ways in Squeak Smalltalk to serialize and store objects.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The easiest and most used are `storeOn:/readFrom:` and binary storage formats based on `SmartRefStream` serializers.
[src:ndjson/serialization] In addition, bundled objects can be stored and retrieved using `ImageSegments`.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Both provide a so-called "binary-object storage framework", which support serialization into and retrieval from a compact binary form.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Both handle cyclic, recursive and shared structures, storage/retrieval of class and metaclass info and include mechanisms for "on the fly" object migration (i.e. to convert instances which were written by an older version of a class with a different object layout).
[src:ndjson/serialization] The APIs are similar (storeBinary/readBinary), but the encoding details are different, making these two formats incompatible.
[src:ndjson/serialization] However, the Smalltalk/X code is open source and free and can be loaded into other Smalltalks to allow for cross-dialect object interchange.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Object serialization is not part of the ANSI Smalltalk specification.
[src:ndjson/serialization] As a result, the code to serialize an object varies by Smalltalk implementation.
[src:ndjson/serialization] For instance, a serialized object created in Squeak Smalltalk cannot be restored in Ambrai Smalltalk.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Consequently, various applications that do work on multiple Smalltalk implementations that rely on object serialization cannot share data between these different implementations.
[src:ndjson/serialization] These applications include the MinneStore object database and some RPC packages.
[src:ndjson/serialization] A solution to this problem is SIXX, which is a package for multiple Smalltalks that uses an XML-based format for serialization.
[src:ndjson/serialization] The Swift standard library provides two protocols, `Encodable` and `Decodable` (composed together as `Codable`), which allow instances of conforming types to be serialized to or deserialized from JSON, property lists, or other formats.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Default implementations of these protocols can be generated by the compiler for types whose stored properties are also `Decodable` or `Encodable`.
[src:ndjson/serialization] PowerShell implements serialization through the built-in cmdlet `Export-CliXML`.
[src:ndjson/serialization] `Export-CliXML` serializes .NET objects and stores the resulting XML in a file.
[src:ndjson/serialization] To reconstitute the objects, use the `Import-CliXML` cmdlet, which generates a deserialized object from the XML in the exported file.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Deserialized objects, often known as "property bags" are not live objects; they are snapshots that have properties, but no methods.
[src:ndjson/serialization] Two dimensional data structures can also be (de)serialized in CSV format using the built-in cmdlets `Import-CSV` and `Export-CSV`.
